<paragraph id="9A6A0C04FFE79A62FF5EFEF8FCB4CE25" blockId="2.[136,1452,236,677]" box="[189,790,340,365]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">
Host Plant. 
<taxonomicName id="5DD57787FFE79A62FED8FEF9FD38CE24" authority="(Trin.) Bor" authorityName="Bor" baseAuthorityName="Trin." box="[315,666,340,364]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Psammochloa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="A8A1D016FFE79A62FED8FEF9FD82CE24" box="[315,544,340,364]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Psammochloa villosa</emphasis>
(Trin.) Bor
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="02EE1081FFE79A62FD4AFEF9FCA8CE25" box="[681,778,340,365]" captionStart="Figures 7–10" captionStartId="3.[155,227,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figures 7–10. Biological pictures of Eodorcadion (Ornatodorcadion) zhaoi sp. nov. 7. Male on the food plant. 8. Female before oviposition. 9–10. Landscape of the localities." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5360850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5360850/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9A6A0C04FFE79A62FF5EFEDAFAE0CD74" blockId="2.[136,1452,236,677]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">
Biology. Adults are active in the daytime in the sandy deserts (
<figureCitation id="02EE1081FFE79A62FCBEFEDAFC68CEC7" box="[861,970,375,399]" captionStart="Figures 7–10" captionStartId="3.[155,227,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figures 7–10. Biological pictures of Eodorcadion (Ornatodorcadion) zhaoi sp. nov. 7. Male on the food plant. 8. Female before oviposition. 9–10. Landscape of the localities." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5360850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5360850/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Figs 9–10</figureCitation>
) from the middle of August to the beginning of October; the first specimen collected on 
<date id="EE6B2AC4FFE79A62FDB2FE37FD14CEFA" box="[593,694,410,434]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" value="2017-10-01">1.X.2017</date>
, was found at 10: 00 am, while those collected on 
<date id="EE6B2AC4FFE79A62FB29FE37FA8FCEFA" box="[1226,1325,410,434]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" value="2018-10-03">3.X.2018</date>
were found during 9:30–15:00 eating leaves and stems of 
<taxonomicName id="5DD57787FFE79A62FD89FE11FBEDCE9C" authority="(Trin.) Bor. Oviposition" authorityName="Bor. Oviposition" baseAuthorityName="Trin." box="[618,1103,444,468]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Psammochloa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="A8A1D016FFE79A62FD89FE11FCECCE9C" box="[618,846,444,468]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Psammochloa villosa</emphasis>
(Trin.) Bor. Oviposition
</taxonomicName>
takes place on bases of the stems of host plants. Beetles try to escape by quick crawling (cannot fly for hind wings reduced). One individual was videoed on 
<date id="EE6B2AC4FFE79A62FF6BFDAFFEB7CD52" box="[136,277,514,538]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" value="2018-08-19">19.VIII.2018</date>
, at the locality which is beside the Tian’ehu (Swan lake) of Alxa Left Banner, Tengger Desert (personal communication with Li Ren and Bao Li, video taken by Jun Du), showing that it can crawl quite fast on the sand.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9A6A0C04FFE79A62FF5EFDEAFDF0CD17" blockId="2.[136,1452,236,677]" box="[189,594,583,607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">
Distribution. 
<collectingCountry id="E2C24C94FFE79A62FEAFFDEAFE2ECD17" box="[332,396,583,607]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="5811C2E6FFE79A62FE7AFDEAFDE5CD17" box="[409,583,583,607]" country="China" name="Nei Mongol" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Inner Mongolia</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9A6A0C04FFE79A62FF5EFDC7FD22CDEC" blockId="2.[136,1452,236,677]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">
Etymology. The species is named after Mr. Xinxin Zhao (
<collectingRegion id="5811C2E6FFE79A62FCC5FDC7FC73CDCA" box="[806,977,618,642]" country="China" name="Nei Mongol" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Inner Mongolia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="E2C24C94FFE79A62FC3EFDC7FB83CDCA" box="[989,1057,618,642]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">China</collectingCountry>
), who collected the first specimen of the 
<typeStatus id="456EB2A6FFE79A62FF53FD20FF7CCDED" box="[176,222,653,677]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">type</typeStatus>
series and kindly donated it to 
<collectionCode id="FCC494C1FFE79A62FDCFFD21FDDECDEC" box="[556,636,652,676]" country="China" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/crjh-4ne1" name="Institute of Zoology, Chinese Academy of Sciences" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">IZCAS</collectionCode>
.
</paragraph>
